author: scurest
message:
Import: factor out code for creating texture shader nodes

The code that creates the string of UV Map -> Mapping -> Tex Img
nodes is now in one place. Removes many bugs and inconsistencies
in the duplicated code, and nice code size reduction too.

Also removes all the existing code for storing textureInfo stuff
on texture or info objects, or setting the name of UV layers from
the mesh classes (the name was always just TEXCOORD_n anyway).
IOW, it only needs to look at the textureInfo object to create
the needed nodes.

message:
CI: find the latest 2.8X Blender version for blender28 targets

This will fetch https://builder.blender.org and try to find out
the latest 2.8X version of Blender. This broke after 2.81 was
released and builder.blender.org only had URLs for 2.82.

This should keep us going throughout 2.89. CI will break again
if Blender 2.9 or 3.0 comes out, but the tests will also break
in that case anyway, since "28" is also hardcoded there.

author: scurest
message:
Import: bugfix for skinned mesh normals not being normalized

Forgot to renormalize normals after skinning them into the bind
pose.

This manifested as tris being marked flat in skinned meshes with
scalings, since the code for marking polys flat depends on the
maximum dot product being 1.

author: scurest
message:
Import: fix issue involving flipped bone Z dir (#1396)

In some cases, setting the editbone length can flip its Z dir.
This avoids the issue by setting the length first, then setting
the Z dir (with align_roll).

See #1396 for additional info.

See T88581 for the upstream Blender issue.

author: scurest
message:
Export: detect when a file will be overwritten

In the file select dialogue for the exporter, the filename should
be red when there's an existing file that will be overwritten.

Before this we only used the stem of the filename (ie a not a.glb)
so it wouldn't detect that a.glb would be overwritten.

This changes it to use the full filename with the extension. The
filename has to be updated when either the name or format option
changes.

author: scurest
message:
Export: add option to export textures into a folder

For the "glTF Separate" format, you can now pick a path relative
to the location of the .gltf to put texture files in. Defaults to
the empty path, ie. the same folder as the .gltf, so there's no
change in the default behaviour.

Since the __add_image function needed to know the output path,
this takes the suggestion from the TODO there and passes the
export options to the constructor of the Exporter object.

author: scurest
message:
Export: handle edge cases in ExportGltf2.check

thus the other exporters) works.

In GLB mode:

   Filename '' becomes '' (before it became '.glb')
   Filename '.glb' becomes '.glb' (before it became '.glb.glb')
   Filename '.gltf' becomes '.glb' (before it became '.gltf.glb')

author: scurest
message:
Import: fix bug with animated armature objects

Bones use a cache to all put their channel in an action on the
armature object. But objects were (erroneously) not using the
cache, so an armature object could wind up with two actions, one
with pose bone stuff and one with its own loc/rot/scale.

Order of preference is now

* image.name
* if the image is in a file, the filename

place this was used was in BlenderImage. It's simpler if BlenderImage
picks the name itself.

author: scurest
message:
Export: support KHR_materials_unlit

Detects if a material has a "shadeless" graph and exports
with KHR_materials_unlit if it does.

The shadeless graph we recognize is based off a popularly-
recommended setup found on blender.stackexchange.com
(serach for "shadeless").

KHR_materials_unlit now round-trips through the importer.

author: jim-ec
message:
Fix #440 and #445

When two Blender objects share vertex data (for example by duplicating
with alt-d), two meshes reference the same mesh object.
The problem was that the shared index buffer was deleted after the
first node was compressed and the second node tried to reference that
deleted index buffer afterwards.

author: scurest
message:
Export: export EXTEND textures as CLAMP_TO_EDGE

CLIP textures were being exported as CLAMP_TO_EDGE. CLIP (which
says that outside the texture boundaries all pixels are
transparent) can't be done in glTF. EXTEND is the right one for
this.

author: scurest
message:
Import: bugfix for pyscenes with no nodes

Algorithm is the same if all glTF scenes have nodes properties.
We now look for the first vnode in this list that exists

* the first node in the default glTF scene
* the first node in the first glTF scene
* the first node in the second glTF scene
* ...
* the root vnode if it is an object
* the first child of the root vnode

author: scurest
message:
Export: correctly handle empty/OOB material slots

If material_index >= number of material slots, the old code would
export this as material: None. This fixes it to use the last material
slot, which is what Blender does.

Also because slots without a material were skipped in the material_names
list, this messed up material indices. Now empty material slots export
with material: None.

author: scurest
message:
CI: find the latest 2.8X Blender version for blender28 targets

This will fetch https://builder.blender.org and try to find out
the latest 2.8X version of Blender. This broke after 2.81 was
released and builder.blender.org only had URLs for 2.82.

This should keep us going throughout 2.89. CI will break again
if Blender 2.9 or 3.0 comes out, but the tests will also break
in that case anyway, since "28" is also hardcoded there.

author: scurest
message:
Import: use numpy for accessor decoding

Future code can use decode_accessor to get data as numpy arrays.

Note that this also changes get_data_from_accessor to return a
list of lists, rather than a list of tuples.

Removes support for MAT2/3 (not that it matters though; they aren't
used).

author: scurest
message:
Import/Perf: ensure normalized accessors decode to float32s

This makes a significant performance difference in foreach_set.

author: scurest
message:
Import: remove "husks" left behind when moving skinned meshes

When a skinned mesh is moved to a child of its arma, the old node
where it was may be left with no purpose, becoming an empty "husk".
When it won't mess up anything (animations, other children, etc)
we can move the entire node to become a child of the arma instead.

One very important consequence: when round-tripping, even if a
skinned mesh does get moved to a new node on the *first* import,
on all subsequent imports, it can stay at that node, with no
further changes to the node tree.

author: scurest
message:
Import: remove Yup2Zup node for good

Apply coordinate conversions whenever we read coordinates from the
glTF file, allowing us to remove the Yup2Zup node.

In debug mode, the conversion functions don't do the Yup2Zup
conversion.

A vnode pass was added to move cameras/lights to fresh children
with an appropriate correction factor for the differing conventions
about what axes they point on, just like how the exporter works.

author: scurest
message:
Export: don't write empty buffer

When the buffer is empty for an export, GLBs would already skip
writing the BIN chunk, but there would still be a Buffer in the
JSON with a byteLength of 0 (which is illegal) and .gltfs would
still write out an empty .bin file.

This fixes these two points.

author: scurest
message:
Export: export EXTEND textures as CLAMP_TO_EDGE

CLIP textures were being exported as CLAMP_TO_EDGE. CLIP (which
says that outside the texture boundaries all pixels are
transparent) can't be done in glTF. EXTEND is the right one for
this.

author: scurest
message:
Exporter: correctly convert UV texture transforms

Previous to this change, the values in the Mapping node in Blender
were copied straight into the KHR_texture_transform object. This
is incorrect because the Mapping node is applied in Blender's UV
space, which is related to glTF's with the u,v->u,1-v conversion.
That meant that a Mapping node that translates up would be exported
as a KHR_texture_transform that translates down because of the
differing directions of the V axis.

The correct thing to do is to calculate the equivalent transform
in the other UV space.

This was added to the common module because the importer would
need to apply the same conversion to get the right Mapping node
from a KHR_texture_transform.

In case binary file is not included in Blender3D installation it would be nice for user to know the fastest way to solve the problem without visiting source files.

My case is that Blender3D uses OS Python libraries and adding ```blender_root / python_lib / python_version / 'site_packages'``` folder to my installation breaks Python or some of it's dependencies. Adding BLENDER_EXTERN_DRACO_LIBRARY_PATH with binary file is the fastest way to solve a problem.

author: scurest
message:
Import: separate the notion of {bind pose TR, editbone TR, node TR}

Doesn't change anything, but refactors for future changes/clarity.

Clearly separates the following properties of a bone

* Bind pose trans/rot. Meshes are retargeted onto this pose.
* Editbone trans/rot. Used to compute edit bone positions and to
  compute the pose bone we need given a desired final TRS.
* Node trans/rot. This is what was being used for the above.

Code was all updated to use whichever of these notions is right
for it.

A new vnode pass was added to pick the bind pose we want to use.
Currently it initializes it to the node trans/rot, so there's no
change.

author: scurest
message:
Import: massive improvement to skinning / node hierarchy

Introduces an intermediate data structure, a graph of "virtual"
nodes, that gives us a lot of flexibility in manipulating the
node graph before we create the "real" Blender nodes.

A series of passes transforms the glTF node graph into something
we can import into Blender.

Skinned meshes are also moved to their armature and hard-skinned
into their bind position at mesh creation time.

Together all this fixes all the skinning issues I could find.

Some stuff was dropped (scenes/collections, Yup2Zup removal,
selecting/active, bone chains) for simplicity. Can be worked
on later.

author: scurest
message:
Export: less naive JPEG detection

The check image.file_format == 'JPEG' was apparently too naive to
detect real JPEGs. Photoshop .psd files also have this property.
Reading the docs, file_format is the format the image should be
*re-saved* as, not the file format it actually had.

The new check goes back to using the file extension. Should be
okay, since the importer adds file extensions to its temp files
now, so they get detected correctly. (This was the main problem
with using file extensions before.)

author: scurest
message:
Import: simplify/cleanup image importing

Use D.images.load(check_existing=True) to check for existing images
instead of looping ourselves.

Guard the tempfile with a finally clause so it always gets cleaned
up.

Previously for the "Pack images" option, an image from a file did
  read file -> write to tempfile -> load tempfile -> pack -> erase tempfile
Now we do just
  load file -> pack

Perf: faster Import > Shading > Use Normal Data

This shaves off ~40-50% of the time to do the Use Normal Data
calculations in my tests.

It is *not* exactly the same as before. The differences are:

* It uses poly.normal instead of calculating the normal from
  the vertex coords. These are not the same, but they are
  really, really close. OTOH, the comparison to 0.9999999 is
  so sensitive, it can tell them apart.

* It considers all the vertices in the poly instead of only three,
  but this doesn't change anything at the moment because only tris
  are imported.

author: scurest
message:
Export: avoid pointless image<->Python data conversions

Previously all images were decoded to a Python tuple of 4*w*h floats
and put into a numpy array. This was so the channels could be
assembled together for eg. metallicRoughness textures. After assembly,
the numpy array would then be converted back to a tuple, fed into the
image.pixels of a new Blender image, the image saved, and the encoded
image read back.

A special path handled images that were already saved on disk;
the file on disk would just be read, skipping the final
array->tuple->image conversion, but the initial conversion
image->tuple->array was always performed.

For most images this is wasted time and memory. The channels aren't
going to be changed, so we could have just used the original image!

So this commit makes ExportImage smarter. It now stores a description
of how its intended image should be built instead of an array of
pixel values. For example, it says its R channel should be filled by
the G channel of such-and-such image.

Then when we go to encode, we have enough information to make better
decisions about how to do it. There is a "happy path" where we
can just use an existing Blender image and don't ever have to
convert to Python data. The "unhappy" path, where we do have to
assemble an image out of channel, however, remains the same.

The happy path should contain all color image (baseColor, emission),
normal maps, and metal-rough-occlusion textures that are already
packed the way the exporter likes.

Knocks about 50% off the export time for models with lots of texture
data, and reduces memory usage.

author: scurest
message:
Export: workaround for #932

Removes the workaround added by f2f3b83.

Sometimes calling gather_material invalidates the blender_mesh
being used by gather_mesh.

This just swaps the order of gather_primitives and gather_weights.
The blender_mesh is now never accessed again after gather_material
is called.

author: scurest
message:
Export: handle different-sized images in ExportImage

When combining image channels, scale all images to the output
image dimensions before combining.

The output image width is the max of all input image widths (and
similarly for the height), so images are always scaled up, never
down (which would be lossy).

Probably still better to have them all be the same size though
(as far as efficiency)...

author: scurest
message:
Import: rewrite material code

Rewrites material code as functions which each make one "piece" of
the node tree, taking the location to create at and the sockets to
attach to as arguments. Results in better composability.

Several bugs were fixed. Notably the base color term is now
calculated correctly, nodes are layed out properly, and the
pbrSpecularGlossiness setup is improved.

author: scurest
message:
Export: don't combine image names if they're all from the same file

Fix #1014

Before this, if there was one image in an ExportImage, we'd try to
use its filename as the image name. This generalizes this to when
there's one filepath (ie. multiple images with the same filepath).

The __gather_name function was also changed to examine the ExportImage
rather than traverse the node graph, which is simpler.

author: scurest
message:
Export/Refactor: add TmpImageGuard for cleaning up temp images

Adds an RAII-style guard class. Replaces this

  tmp_image = None
  try:
      tmp_image = INIT
      BODY
  finally:
      if tmp_image is not None:
          cleanup tmp_image

with this

  with TmpImageGuard() as guard:
      guard.image = INIT
      tmp_image = guard.image
      BODY

Used to safely abstract out the _make_temp_image_copy function.

author: scurest
message:
Export: stopgap for zero-weight verts producing invalid files

Verts without any vertex group assignments currently export
with zero weights, which is invalid and renders differently in
different viewers.

This is a stopgap that produces a valid file. It does the same
thing the Three.js viewer does; treat these verts as assigned
to the 0th joint.

These verts SHOULD act as if they weren't skinned and this
commit does NOT FIX that (unless the root bone happens to have
a default transform, so that verts skinned by it happen to
act as if they weren't skinned).

or from a MULTIPLY node in front of the socket.

This is used for baseColorFactor, roughnessFactor, etc. The test
from the last commit now passes.

The RGB part of baseColorFactor already had code for this that
worked differently (it didn't require MULTIPLY be right in front
of the socket and it required there be a texture). A log statement
was also dropped.s
